[laughs] I know,
I know, right? Um...

11:55.018 --> 11:57.238
Thing is, um...

11:57.281 --> 11:59.762
And I hate

11:59.806 --> 12:03.461
putting you
in this position, but...

12:03.505 --> 12:05.899
Thing is, there's gonna be
a dark cloud over Mama

12:05.942 --> 12:07.291
all night if you're not there,

12:07.335 --> 12:09.772
you know?

12:09.816 --> 12:11.818
Cordi... [sighs]

12:11.861 --> 12:13.558
It's not that simple.Geri,

12:13.602 --> 12:15.735
is there anything I can do

12:15.778 --> 12:16.997
to help? Anything?Can you square

12:17.040 --> 12:19.956
the fact that the father I love

12:20.000 --> 12:23.177
killed the man who brought me
into this world only to

12:23.220 --> 12:25.962
throw me out like trash?
[chuckles]

12:26.006 --> 12:28.095
Or-or maybe go back
so that your mom

12:28.138 --> 12:30.184
didn't sit
on that secret?

12:30.227 --> 12:31.925
And, again,

12:31.968 --> 12:33.665
I understand,

12:33.709 --> 12:35.319
but...

12:35.363 --> 12:37.800
I can't undo

12:37.844 --> 12:40.150
how it makes me feel.

12:40.194 --> 12:42.196
Yeah, yeah, I-I get that.

12:42.239 --> 12:43.545
I do. Um...

12:43.588 --> 12:46.417
Just consider it
for them, please.

12:48.332 --> 12:50.508
I will consider it.

12:50.552 --> 12:52.380
Thanks.

12:52.423 --> 12:55.557
For them and you, okay?Yup.

12:57.733 --> 13:00.127
Okay. I'll see you later.

13:00.170 --> 13:02.738
See you.[cell phone ringing]

13:07.569 --> 13:09.614
Walker.

13:09.658 --> 13:11.573
Wait, whoa, whoa.
Whoa, whoa, whoa, hold on.

13:11.616 --> 13:13.096
Wait, Twyla... what?

13:16.099 --> 13:18.406
Okay, uh... Hang tight.

13:18.449 --> 13:20.190
I'm on my way.

13:31.506 --> 13:34.248
You're saying $800
just happened to disappear

13:34.291 --> 13:35.771
on your first day?TWYLA: Exactly.

13:35.815 --> 13:36.990
It's my first day.

13:37.033 --> 13:38.382
I know how to hide a con
better than that.

13:38.426 --> 13:40.036
Hey, uh,
Ranger Cordell Walker.

13:40.080 --> 13:41.690
Um, I'm here. Officer.

13:41.733 --> 13:44.040
Uh, I'm...
What's going on?

13:44.084 --> 13:45.563
[scoffs] I'll tell you
what's going on,

13:45.607 --> 13:47.783
she thought she could
take me for a ride.

13:47.827 --> 13:50.177
Thought I wouldn't notice
her misdirecting

13:50.220 --> 13:52.919
electronic funds transfers
right under my nose.

13:52.962 --> 13:55.051
Oh, if I took you for a ride,
you'd know it, buddy.

13:55.095 --> 13:56.400
Okay, okay,
Twyla, cool it.

13:56.444 --> 13:57.793
Cool it.

13:57.837 --> 13:59.621
BOSS: There's nothing left
to solve here. A criminal

13:59.664 --> 14:01.710
with prior felony
theft convictions

14:01.753 --> 14:03.190
thought she'd
try it again,

14:03.233 --> 14:04.800
but not today.

14:04.844 --> 14:07.890
Take her away.Nah, no, no. Not so fast.

14:07.934 --> 14:09.892
[phone chimes]No one is putting Twyla
behind bars

14:09.936 --> 14:11.198
without her getting
a fair shake,

14:11.241 --> 14:12.895
you understand that?

14:12.939 --> 14:15.289
H-Hold on a second, okay?
Just, um...

14:16.681 --> 14:18.901
Everybody just hang tight

14:18.945 --> 14:21.295
for a minute, okay?
I have to address this.

14:24.602 --> 14:26.909
[cell phone ringing]Mm.

14:26.953 --> 14:28.476
What up, stinker?

14:28.519 --> 14:30.347
You texted me SOS. What's up?

14:30.391 --> 14:34.395
Yeah, the berries
are clogged in the dispenser

14:34.438 --> 14:35.918
for my Bourbon
Blackberry Collins.

14:35.962 --> 14:38.616
You don't text "SOS"
over a-a bourbon...

14:38.660 --> 14:40.053
[stammers] What?

14:40.096 --> 14:41.924
The signature cocktail
that I'm...

14:41.968 --> 14:44.796
I made just in case
we can't get the champagne.

14:44.840 --> 14:46.668
I don't really have time
for this right now, Liam.

14:46.711 --> 14:48.713
Uh... [stammers]
I'm trying to keep Twyla

14:48.757 --> 14:50.324
out of jail, so...

14:50.367 --> 14:53.283
Twyla? You're with Twyla
right now? Second time

14:53.327 --> 14:54.763
in one week.
Hey, you better pray

14:54.806 --> 14:57.157
that Mom and Dad or Geri
don't catch wind of this.

14:57.200 --> 14:58.288
Don't start, all right?

14:58.332 --> 14:59.333
I'm just doing my job.

14:59.376 --> 15:00.725
Hey, I'm serious about Geri.

15:00.769 --> 15:02.597
This is not a good way
to make peace.

15:02.640 --> 15:04.033
Does she know
that you're with Twyla?

15:04.077 --> 15:06.079
There's nothing to know, Liam.

15:06.122 --> 15:08.559
A-And Geri and I a-aren't even,

15:08.603 --> 15:10.039
like... [stammers]Yeah, I know, I know,

15:10.083 --> 15:12.868
but Twyla equals Rodeo Kings.

15:12.912 --> 15:15.262
She was all over
the news cycle, and I-I know

15:15.305 --> 15:16.872
that she had nothing to do
with Hoyt's death

15:16.916 --> 15:18.918
and that whole nightmare, but...

15:18.961 --> 15:20.267
I don't think that Geri's

15:20.310 --> 15:21.659
gonna be able
to make that distinction.

15:21.703 --> 15:23.400
Liam, I got this.

15:28.231 --> 15:29.929
Secret to brisket
is to get a good sear

15:29.972 --> 15:31.234
before it slow roasts.

15:31.278 --> 15:32.496
You're gonna school me
on brisket?

15:32.540 --> 15:33.889
Well...I've been searing

15:33.933 --> 15:35.195
your brisket for months now.

15:35.238 --> 15:36.979
Mm.
What?

15:37.023 --> 15:38.459
What I want to know

15:38.502 --> 15:41.157
is the spice ratio
in that chili of yours.

15:41.201 --> 15:43.029
I-I nearly forgot,

15:43.072 --> 15:46.075
you're the one who's been
prepping and-and-and serving

15:46.119 --> 15:48.251
at The Side Step
this whole time. Wow.
Mm-hmm.

15:48.295 --> 15:50.471
Well, I guess this,
uh, chili has been

15:50.514 --> 15:52.908
in family hands this whole time.
Imagine that.

15:52.952 --> 15:55.432
Hadn't thought
about it that way.Yeah. Mm-hmm.

15:55.476 --> 15:56.999
Mm. Okay,

15:57.043 --> 15:59.001
you get the spices
I'll get the pot,

15:59.045 --> 16:01.047
and, uh, we'll swap secrets,
all right?

16:01.090 --> 16:03.005
Okay.
Okay.

16:03.049 --> 16:04.789
Here we go. Whew.

16:04.833 --> 16:07.357
Let's go with this one.Oh. They used to...

16:07.401 --> 16:08.532
I moved them.

16:08.576 --> 16:09.969
Here we go.

16:10.012 --> 16:12.014
Right here.

16:12.058 --> 16:14.277
[sighs] Mm...

16:14.321 --> 16:16.323
So, I'll get this one.

16:16.366 --> 16:18.281
Oregano.

16:18.325 --> 16:19.761
You okay, sweetheart?Yeah,

16:19.804 --> 16:21.589
no, I think it's just...

16:21.632 --> 16:23.243
being in this kitchen.

16:23.286 --> 16:24.809
Everything's...
Yeah.

16:24.853 --> 16:26.507
...so different.

16:26.550 --> 16:29.118
Yeah.

16:29.162 --> 16:31.555
A-And it's-it's

16:31.599 --> 16:33.427
Abeline and-and Bonham's

16:33.470 --> 16:34.819
40th anniversary.

16:34.863 --> 16:36.952
[gasps] Oh...And they're celebrating

16:36.996 --> 16:38.214
tonight.
Okay.

16:38.258 --> 16:40.695
They asked me
to be there, so...

16:40.738 --> 16:43.698
All right, well,
I'm-I'm glad you said so.

16:43.741 --> 16:45.830
Uh, look, I-I understand

16:45.874 --> 16:48.007
you have a history
with Bonham and Abby,

16:48.050 --> 16:50.139
of course I do,

16:50.183 --> 16:52.707
and after all the losses
they've been through,

16:52.750 --> 16:54.926
I'd expect they need you
there tonight.

16:54.970 --> 16:56.450
So you should go.

16:56.493 --> 16:57.973
Yeah, you g--
you got my blessing,

16:58.017 --> 16:59.888
not-not that you need it,
of course.

17:01.194 --> 17:02.978
Look, um...

17:03.022 --> 17:06.329
I can't say why Abeline
stayed silent all those years,

17:06.373 --> 17:08.853
but what I can say is

17:08.897 --> 17:11.726
Marv saddled her
with an impossible choice.

17:13.423 --> 17:15.251
Don't let him do
the same thing to you.

17:17.645 --> 17:21.083
Okay, thank you.
Uh... Well, good news,

17:21.127 --> 17:22.737
Mr. O'Brien...
[clears throat]

17:22.780 --> 17:24.391
our financial forensics

17:24.434 --> 17:27.481
tracked down that, uh,
$800 in misallocated EFTs.

17:27.524 --> 17:29.439
Mm-hmm.
Bad news,

17:29.483 --> 17:31.746
looks like it was
your clerical error.What?

17:31.789 --> 17:33.487
[sighs] Regardless,
you can't

17:33.530 --> 17:34.836
blame me for looking
at her record

17:34.879 --> 17:36.142
and coming to the conclusion...

17:36.185 --> 17:37.273
Oh, I can, and I am.

17:37.317 --> 17:38.405
Your oversight

17:38.448 --> 17:40.102
could've upended
her life.

17:40.146 --> 17:42.191
All I need to know
is that she...

17:42.235 --> 17:44.106
WALKER: Is that she's trying
to turn her life around.

17:44.150 --> 17:45.629
That she's
a STEM grant recipient

17:45.673 --> 17:47.718
who took a job
to make ends meet.

17:47.762 --> 17:50.678
Do you think she worked all
those years to-to case a bank?

17:50.721 --> 17:52.984
Twyla trusted

17:53.028 --> 17:56.205
the wrong guy, and it
backfired and snowballed.

17:56.249 --> 17:57.554
She's paid
for it already.

17:57.598 --> 18:00.557
She doesn't need to pay
for the rest of her life.

18:00.601 --> 18:03.125
I'll check in
with you tomorrow.

18:03.169 --> 18:05.214
Okay.

18:09.088 --> 18:10.959
[door opens]

18:13.875 --> 18:14.876
[sighs]

18:14.919 --> 18:16.007
[exhales]

18:18.836 --> 18:21.100
Two Perezes, one Austin.

18:21.143 --> 18:23.798
This town
ain't weird enough

18:23.841 --> 18:25.887
for the both of us.

18:27.845 --> 18:30.674
Look, Mom made it sound like
you hadn't put down roots yet.

18:32.589 --> 18:34.504
Well, I wasn't gonna
stay in Houston

18:34.548 --> 18:36.332
after Lucas.

18:38.726 --> 18:40.423
Oh, you're still here?

18:40.467 --> 18:42.730
Figured you would've run
at the mention of his name.

18:43.948 --> 18:46.473
All right, okay.
Well, I deserve that.

18:46.516 --> 18:48.039
[sighs]

18:48.083 --> 18:49.824
Look, I'm trying
to fix this.

18:49.867 --> 18:52.348
Just let me explain
what happened.

18:52.392 --> 18:54.176
I know what happened.
I was there.

18:54.220 --> 18:56.483
I watched my boyfriend die.
Where the hell were you?

18:56.526 --> 18:58.963
I was trying to...

18:59.007 --> 19:00.835
Pretend nothing was happening?

19:03.185 --> 19:05.187
Um... [groans]

19:05.231 --> 19:07.711
Okay, right, okay. Um...

19:07.755 --> 19:10.801
Let's just stick to the
champagne my friend asked about,

19:10.845 --> 19:12.629
okay? Did you get it?

19:14.065 --> 19:15.415
His family
needs my help.

19:15.458 --> 19:16.633
Oh, his family?

19:16.677 --> 19:18.461
Wow, how selfless,
Cass.

19:18.505 --> 19:19.984
What a friend.
I'm sure everything

19:20.028 --> 19:21.377
will go great for them
with you in their corner.

19:21.421 --> 19:23.597
You know what...No, I don't.

19:23.640 --> 19:27.427
Oh, is this when you
send a postcard?

19:31.039 --> 19:33.172
He asked about you,
you know.

19:35.043 --> 19:36.653
Near the end,
he asked about you.

19:37.828 --> 19:39.961
I never really knew
what to say.

19:40.004 --> 19:41.528
Lucky for you,
he was so far gone

19:41.571 --> 19:43.138
he never really
knew the truth.

19:59.633 --> 20:01.852
You're okay, you're okay.

20:01.896 --> 20:03.941
[crying]

20:05.116 --> 20:06.335
Uh...

20:08.642 --> 20:09.686
[grunts]

20:22.656 --> 20:25.615
My goodness, you look as
beautiful as the day we met.

20:28.357 --> 20:30.838
You know, everything's gonna be
all right in time,

20:30.881 --> 20:33.493
so let's just

20:33.536 --> 20:35.146
enjoy the night.

20:35.190 --> 20:36.452
I know.

20:38.062 --> 20:40.543
What do you think
they got planned for us?

20:40.587 --> 20:43.154
Viking funeral.
[laughs]

20:43.198 --> 20:44.852
So be it.

20:44.895 --> 20:47.420
As long as I sail out
with you.

20:47.463 --> 20:49.160
[chuckles]

20:55.123 --> 20:57.734
Dad seemed super bummed
to miss dinner tonight,

20:57.778 --> 20:59.562
but he had a ton
of work stuff.

20:59.606 --> 21:03.436
Anyways, it should be fun with
just us and Uncle Liam, right?

21:03.479 --> 21:04.654
Of course it will.
Won't it, hon?

21:04.698 --> 21:05.960
ABELINE:Oh, yes.

21:06.003 --> 21:07.396
Oh, crap. Hey, guys,
I just got a text

21:07.440 --> 21:09.311
that, uh,
Uncle Liam's stuck

21:09.355 --> 21:10.660
in traffic.
He said he won't be able

21:10.704 --> 21:12.314
to make dinner either.Oh.

21:12.358 --> 21:13.576
Oh, what a shame.

21:13.620 --> 21:14.664
[sighs]ABELINE: You know,

21:14.708 --> 21:16.057
since it's just
the four of us,

21:16.100 --> 21:18.059
why don't we just swing by
a-a food truck?

21:18.102 --> 21:19.321
Oh, I'm craving
Patrizi's.

21:19.365 --> 21:20.583
Oh, Patrizi's.

21:20.627 --> 21:22.063
Yeah, that'd
hit the spot.

21:22.106 --> 21:24.848
Oh, um,
I'm gluten-free now,

21:24.892 --> 21:26.589
so Italian
really might not be

21:26.633 --> 21:29.026
the best...
BONHAM: Oh, well,
you know, tacos

21:29.070 --> 21:30.680
is always a good anniversary
meal, isn't it?

21:30.724 --> 21:32.029
Well, you know,
a-and-and

21:32.073 --> 21:34.205
Rosarito's
has got corn tortillas.

21:34.249 --> 21:35.946
I left my prescription
at the bar.

21:35.990 --> 21:37.383
Oh!Why would you leave
your prescription?

21:37.426 --> 21:39.559
I didn't know you took
a prescription.
Yeah, no,

21:39.602 --> 21:40.603
it's-it's
really vital.

21:40.647 --> 21:41.822
I just forget
the name of it. Um...

21:41.865 --> 21:43.911
It's at The Side Step,
so let's go to the...

21:43.954 --> 21:45.478
uh, Side Step.Well, we're right here,

21:45.521 --> 21:47.393
so it's no problem,
Augie. [chuckles]

21:47.436 --> 21:49.743
We might as well
just all go inside.

21:49.786 --> 21:51.310
ABELINE:
Well, we could stay in the car.

21:51.353 --> 21:52.876
AUGUST:
[stammers] Let's go inside.

21:52.920 --> 21:55.096
STELLA: I don't think
that's a great idea. Yeah.

21:57.403 --> 21:59.056
CROWD:
Surprise!

21:59.100 --> 22:00.275
[cheering]

22:00.319 --> 22:03.496
Thank you. Hey...

22:03.539 --> 22:05.976
Hey, you, too.
What's going on?

22:07.282 --> 22:09.458
[Abeline laughs]

22:11.634 --> 22:14.245
Happy anniversary, Daddy, Mama.

22:14.289 --> 22:15.682
LIAM:We're so proud to
have you as parents.

22:15.725 --> 22:17.379
We love you so much.

22:17.423 --> 22:19.338
WALKER: Mama. All right, come
on. Yeah, yeah. Bring it in.

22:19.381 --> 22:20.643
Hey. Big hug.

22:20.687 --> 22:22.689
[cheering, applause]

22:24.255 --> 22:27.258
All right, all right.
Eat, drink, be merry.

22:27.302 --> 22:28.303
Open bar.

22:28.347 --> 22:29.652
[cheering, applause]

22:29.696 --> 22:31.567
Whoa, that's a good sign.
How's it going?

22:31.611 --> 22:34.962
Uh, hey, Lou, can I get another
Bourbon Blackberry Collins?

22:35.005 --> 22:36.006
Gotcha.

22:36.050 --> 22:38.400
Thanks.

22:38.444 --> 22:39.923
I got what you were looking for.

22:39.967 --> 22:42.230
Hey.

22:42.273 --> 22:47.191
Uh... Chalamet Esprit Brut
Vintage '82.

22:47.235 --> 22:49.411
A real champagne
in the ass to find

22:49.455 --> 22:51.500
but I finally found it for you.

22:51.544 --> 22:54.808
Wait, a minute, I called
every single wine distributor

22:54.851 --> 22:56.026
in the state of Texas.

22:56.070 --> 22:58.768
How did you get this?

22:58.812 --> 23:00.379
A long story for another day.

23:00.422 --> 23:03.120
I just hope it brings
your folks some joy.

23:03.164 --> 23:05.645
Or, uh, at least a good buzz.

23:05.688 --> 23:07.473
[both chuckle]

23:07.516 --> 23:09.431
Okay, well, thank you.

23:09.475 --> 23:11.651
Thank you. Uh...

23:11.694 --> 23:14.001
Hey, why don't you stick around?

23:14.044 --> 23:16.003
Night's just, uh,
getting started.

23:18.614 --> 23:20.224
Twist my arm.
[chuckles]

23:20.268 --> 23:22.488
LOU:
We're almost out, Liam.

23:22.531 --> 23:24.490
The drink is a hit.

23:24.533 --> 23:26.187
Thank you, Lou.

23:26.230 --> 23:29.277
Um, you know what?

23:29.320 --> 23:32.019
You're a booze expert.

23:32.062 --> 23:34.891
What do you think about this
Bourbon Blackberry Collins?

23:39.330 --> 23:41.811
Mm?

23:41.855 --> 23:43.465
It's a revelation.

23:43.509 --> 23:45.380
This Bourbon Blackberry Collins

23:45.424 --> 23:46.816
changed my life.

23:46.860 --> 23:49.732
Are you pandering
because I made it?

23:49.776 --> 23:51.995
Wait, you crafted this cocktail?

23:52.039 --> 23:53.388
I can't tell if
you're messing with...

23:53.432 --> 23:55.434
No, had I known that you were

23:55.477 --> 23:58.132
the visionary mixologist
of this resplendent...

23:58.175 --> 23:59.699
Okay, I know you're
messing with me.

23:59.742 --> 24:02.615
No, no, no, it's good.
It really is.

24:09.143 --> 24:11.188
It's just a bit acidic.

24:14.931 --> 24:16.498
[tapping on glass]Excuse me.

24:16.542 --> 24:18.152
Folks, folks.

24:18.195 --> 24:19.762
Excuse me.
Thank you, sorry.

24:19.806 --> 24:21.503
I-I wanted to, uh, say,

24:21.547 --> 24:25.638
uh-- I wanted to thank all y'all
for coming out tonight

24:25.681 --> 24:29.032
and, uh, I'd like
to raise a glass

24:29.076 --> 24:32.427
to the beautiful couple
we are all here to celebrate.

24:32.471 --> 24:35.125
[cheering]I-I hear you. I--
My sentiments exactly.

24:35.169 --> 24:38.389
Uh, as lucky as these two are
to have found each other,

24:38.433 --> 24:41.654
I wonder if Liam and I

24:41.697 --> 24:44.047
and my son and daughter

24:44.091 --> 24:48.661
aren't actually
the luckiest people in here,

24:48.704 --> 24:51.359
because we got to have them
as parents,

24:51.402 --> 24:54.580
as-as grandparents.

24:54.623 --> 24:56.712
And we all know
how generous they are

24:56.756 --> 24:59.410
with their love and friendship.

24:59.454 --> 25:00.803
Uh, hear, hear.

25:00.847 --> 25:03.110
[cheering, applause]

25:10.639 --> 25:12.641
ABELINE: Thank you, son.Yeah, just wanted to do

25:12.685 --> 25:13.816
something special
for you tonight.

25:13.860 --> 25:15.557
Um, you know, all the family's

25:15.601 --> 25:17.254
gone through, lately,
a lot of losses, with the ranch

25:17.298 --> 25:19.430
and uprooting the family...Uprooting?

25:19.474 --> 25:21.345
Yeah.Our family, our marriage,

25:21.389 --> 25:23.522
it's-it's not a ranch, son.

25:23.565 --> 25:25.915
Tonight, I'm
remembering...

25:25.959 --> 25:28.352
Hmm. Hmm...Uh-oh.

25:28.396 --> 25:31.181
Uh-oh. [stammers][laughter]

25:31.225 --> 25:32.835
Marriage

25:32.879 --> 25:35.098
is something you grow.

25:35.142 --> 25:37.274
And something we grow.

